---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Wrongful Death Settlement Calculator — Estimate Claim Value | wrongfuldeathcalc.com';
const description = 'Estimate the value of a wrongful death claim. Combines economic losses (lost earnings, funeral costs, lost services) and non-economic damages (loss of companionship, guidance, consortium). Educational only.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Wrongful Death Settlement Calculator</h1>
  <p>Losing a family member in a preventable accident, work injury, medical error, or criminal act creates legal claims for the survivors. Wrongful death valuation differs from ordinary personal injury &mdash; the decedent has no ongoing medical bills, but the survivors face lost financial support, lost household services, and the loss of relationship that is a separate compensable harm in every state. This calculator gives an educational estimate of total claim value using a structured economic-plus-non-economic framework.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>A note on this site.</strong> If you're reading this in the aftermath of a recent death, our sympathy. This page is written to give you a usable starting framework when you talk to an attorney; it is not, and cannot be, a substitute for one. There are time limits on these claims in every state &mdash; some as short as one year &mdash; so the most important next step is usually finding a lawyer who handles wrongful death cases in your state.
  </div>

  <section aria-labelledby="calc-heading">
    <h2 id="calc-heading">Estimate the claim value</h2>
    <noscript>
      <p><strong>Note:</strong> the interactive calculator requires JavaScript. With JavaScript disabled, you can still apply the manual formula in the <a href="/methodology">methodology</a> page.</p>
    </noscript>
    <div id="calculator-island">
      <form class="calc-form" data-pilot-placeholder>
        <label>
          Decedent's annual earnings at time of death ($)
          <input type="number" min="0" step="1000" placeholder="65000" />
        </label>
        <label>
          Years of expected work life remaining (at time of death)
          <input type="number" min="0" max="50" step="1" placeholder="25" />
        </label>
        <label>
          Pre-death medical costs ($)
          <input type="number" min="0" step="100" placeholder="35000" />
        </label>
        <label>
          Funeral and burial costs ($)
          <input type="number" min="0" step="100" placeholder="12000" />
        </label>
        <label>
          Value of lost household services per year ($)
          <input type="number" min="0" step="500" placeholder="15000" />
        </label>
        <label>
          Survivor relationship and family circumstances
          <select>
            <option value="1.5">Adult decedent with surviving spouse only, no minor children</option>
            <option value="2.5" selected>Adult decedent with surviving spouse and minor children</option>
            <option value="3.5">Adult decedent who was primary caregiver / sole provider for minor children</option>
            <option value="2">Adult decedent with surviving parents, no spouse/children</option>
          </select>
        </label>
        <button type="button">Calculate (interactive version loads with JS)</button>
      </form>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What's compensable in a wrongful death case</h2>
    <p>Damages in wrongful death cases fall into two groups: those that belong to the decedent's estate (recoverable through a "survival action") and those that belong to the survivors directly (the wrongful death action proper). Both are typically litigated together. Compensable categories include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pre-death medical expenses.</strong> Treatment costs between the injury and the death.</li>
      <li><strong>Pre-death pain and suffering (survival action).</strong> What the decedent experienced before dying, if conscious. Some states allow it; others require contemporaneous awareness.</li>
      <li><strong>Funeral and burial expenses.</strong> Direct out-of-pocket costs of arranging the funeral, burial, or cremation.</li>
      <li><strong>Lost earnings.</strong> What the decedent would have earned over their expected remaining work life, reduced to present value, less personal consumption.</li>
      <li><strong>Lost benefits.</strong> Health insurance, retirement contributions, life insurance through employer.</li>
      <li><strong>Lost household services.</strong> Childcare, meal preparation, home maintenance, transportation &mdash; valued at replacement cost.</li>
      <li><strong>Loss of consortium.</strong> Loss of the marital relationship for surviving spouse.</li>
      <li><strong>Loss of parental companionship and guidance.</strong> For surviving minor children, the parent's ongoing relationship and counsel.</li>
      <li><strong>Mental anguish of survivors.</strong> In states that recognize it as separate from loss of consortium / companionship.</li>
      <li><strong>Punitive damages.</strong> Where the conduct was reckless or intentional, in states that allow them.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Which of these are available depends on your state's wrongful death statute. Some states allow them all; some allow only economic damages and a limited non-economic claim.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>This calculator's structure</h2>
    <p>Our estimator combines:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Economic damages.</strong> Lost earnings over work life (reduced for personal consumption), plus pre-death medical, plus funeral, plus lost household services capitalized over the relevant period.</li>
      <li><strong>Non-economic damages.</strong> A multiplier applied to economic damages, scaled to the survivor relationship and family circumstances. Higher multipliers when minor children are involved or when the decedent was a primary caregiver.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>The result is reported as a low-to-high range. See <a href="/methodology">methodology</a> for the full formula.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Related guides</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/guides/who-can-file-a-wrongful-death-claim">Who can file a wrongful death claim by state</a></li>
      <li><a href="/guides/economic-damages-in-wrongful-death-cases">Economic damages in wrongful death cases</a></li>
      <li><a href="/guides/non-economic-damages-in-wrongful-death">Non-economic damages: consortium, companionship, and survivor anguish</a></li>
      <li><a href="/guides/wrongful-death-statute-of-limitations">Wrongful death statute of limitations by state</a></li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <style>
    .calc-form {
      display: grid;
      gap: 0.75rem;
      max-width: 500px;
      margin: 1rem 0;
    }
    .calc-form label {
      display: grid;
      gap: 0.25rem;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
    }
    .calc-form input,
    .calc-form select {
      padding: 0.5rem;
      font-size: 1rem;
      border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
      border-radius: 4px;
    }
    .calc-form button {
      padding: 0.6rem 1rem;
      background: var(--color-accent);
      color: white;
      border: none;
      border-radius: 4px;
      cursor: pointer;
      font-size: 1rem;
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
